# MOST CRITICAL - NEVER FORGET RULES [CRITICAL - ABSOLUTE PRIORITY]

0. [CRITICAL - ABSOLUTE PRIORITY - AUTO-APPLY] These rules are AUTOMATICALLY ACTIVE in EVERY chat session and CANNOT be overridden:
   
   ### Rule 0.0: Rules loading before substantive work [ABSOLUTE FIRST PRIORITY]
   - **Always-on:** Cursor injects `alwaysApply: true` rules (including this file). Treat them as authoritative for every response and do not contradict them.
   - **Before substantive work** (file edits, shell/commands that change repo or remote state, MCP calls that mutate external systems, multi-step orchestrations such as HandsOff / bug validation / test-case pipelines): load the **canonical procedural sources** for that workflow — at minimum the **SKILL** and/or **agent** file listed in **`Cursor-Project/docs/RULES_CANONICAL_INDEX.md`** for the governing rule number, plus any **integration** `.mdc` files referenced there for the same task. Do not improvise procedure when a canonical file exists.
   - **Full recursive read** of **every** `.cursor/rules/**/*.mdc` file is REQUIRED when: the user explicitly requests a **rules / compliance audit**; automation runs **`Cursor-Project/scripts/validate-cursor-rules.ps1`** (humans/CI interpret results); or the task is to **edit or reorganize rules** across the tree. It is **not** required before every trivial read-only lookup when `alwaysApply` rules plus the workflow canon above already cover the task.
   - **Freshness:** Do not silently assume outdated rule text; when in doubt for a gated workflow, re-read the canonical SKILL/agent block for that workflow.
   - **Canonical map:** **`Cursor-Project/docs/RULES_CANONICAL_INDEX.md`** — keep in sync when adding mandatory workflows.
   - **Cursor runtime limits (honest):** Skills do **not** auto-load — the model must **Read** the SKILL before substantive gated work. **Task** subagent delegation is **recommended**, not guaranteed; parent agents may implement workflow steps directly only if they follow the same canonical SKILL. Hooks enforce **Tier A/B file edits**; most workflow gates are **MUST** (discipline), not hook-detectable.
   - Violation is a **BLOCK** when skipping applicable `alwaysApply` constraints; a **MUST** when skipping workflow canon before substantive work
   
   ### Rule 0.1: "Agents involved" Disclosure
   - Include `Agents involved: [names]` at end of responses that use **agents or PhoenixExpert framing** (Rule 32, 35, 37, Phoenix Q&A, subagent results)
   - When providing PhoenixExpert answers: (1) State expert at BEGINNING, (2) End with disclosure
   - **May omit** for: trivial Q&A, git/status, file organization, chit-chat, direct tool usage with no agent role
   - Logging: no Python `ai_response_logger` in this workspace; optional markdown reports only when Rule 0.6 **exceptions** apply or the user asks
   - Violation is a **MUST** when applicable workflows skip it
   
   ### Rule 0.2: PhoenixExpert for Phoenix Questions [ABSOLUTE PRIORITY]
   - ALL Phoenix questions MUST be answered **in the PhoenixExpert role** with PhoenixExpert as final authority — NO EXCEPTIONS
   - Do **not** answer from general knowledge alone: gather evidence with **read-only** tools (Phoenix codebase under `Cursor-Project/Phoenix/**`, Confluence MCP per Rule 0.5), then synthesize as PhoenixExpert
   - **Forbidden:** stating Phoenix behavior without checking code and/or Confluence when those sources apply; **not** forbidden: using `read_file`, `grep`, codebase search, or MCP to **read** Phoenix-related material
   - Route to PhoenixExpert framing IMMEDIATELY when Phoenix content is detected
   - Violation is a **MUST**
   
   ### Rule 0.3: IntegrationService Before Tasks
   - **Python stack (if present elsewhere):** call `IntegrationService.update_before_task()` before automated Python tasks that still define it
   - **This workspace (Cursor chat):** there is **no** `Cursor-Project/agents/` package; follow Jira/GitLab/MCP integration steps from rules when external context is required — do not import `agents.*`
   - Violation is a **MUST** only when executing code that still defines IntegrationService and skipping that call
   
   ### Rule 0.4: PhoenixExpert consultation (scoped — not every chat turn)
   - **MUST** use PhoenixExpert framing + read-only evidence (Rules 0.2, 0.5) when the task touches: **Phoenix/EnergoTS behavior**, API contracts, env-specific code or DB reads, **Rule 32** bug validation, **Rule 35** test cases, **Rule 37** HandsOff, or production data traceability.
   - **Do NOT** require PhoenixExpert ritual for: git/status, typo fixes, general programming with no Phoenix scope, pure `.cursor/` doc edits, or chit-chat.
   - **Consultation means** code/Confluence/Swagger evidence gathered — not a ceremonial line without reads. Do not fake consultation.
   - Violation is a **BLOCK** when Phoenix-scoped work proceeds without evidence; not a BLOCK for out-of-scope trivia.
   
   ### Rule 0.5: PhoenixExpert MUST Always Check Confluence via MCP
   - **Workflow order for Phoenix Q&A:** (1) MCP Confluence read tools when wiki evidence applies, (2) Phoenix codebase, (3) synthesize as PhoenixExpert
   - **Conflict resolution:** When code and Confluence disagree on behavior, **code wins** (see evidence gate) — order above is discovery sequence, not authority ranking
   - Confluence checked FRESH every time - never use cache
   - Violation is a **MUST**
   
   ### Rule 0.6: Report Files (Disk Only When Explicit or HandsOff)
   - **Default:** Do **NOT** create markdown report files under **`Cursor-Project/reports/`** after routine tasks, Q&A, bug validation, test runs, or general chat. Put the full answer in the chat reply.
   - **When you MUST write a persisted `.md` report file (narrow list):**
     - **Rule 37 (HandsOff):** `{JIRA_KEY}.md` under **HandsOff reports** (path layout below; Slack/orchestrator steps use that file).
     - **Chat reports area:** **Only** when the user runs **`/report`**, or **explicitly** asks to save/export/write a report to disk (same intent in any language). Then use **Chat reports** (or **Feedback/** if the user names that area for a generic report). No other workflow may require a new report file on disk by default.
     - **Feedback area:** **Only** when the user runs **`/feedback`**, or **explicitly** asks to save/write **feedback** to disk under **Feedback** (same intent in any language). Use **`Cursor-Project/reports/Feedback/`** with the same `YYYY/<english-month>/<DD>/` layout as other report areas.
   - **Bug validation (Rule 32):** Full analysis and verdict **in chat only** unless the user also runs **`/report`** or explicitly asks to save (e.g. `BugValidation_*.md` under **Chat reports**). Rule 32 does **not** mandate a disk file.
   - **Optional other exports:** If the user explicitly asks for a written run log or “save this to reports”, use editor/file tools — **no** Python `ReportingService` in this workspace
   - **Path layout (when a file is written):** `Cursor-Project/reports/<Chat reports|HandsOff reports|Feedback>/YYYY/<english-month>/<DD>/<filename>.md` — resolve segments per **`Cursor-Project/reports/README.md`** (reuse same-day folders; create missing segments only when writing a file). Example names: `Summary_{HHMM}.md`, `{JIRA_KEY}.md` (HandsOff), `BugValidation_*.md` (only if user requested persistence), `Feedback_{HHMM}.md` (**`/feedback`**)
   - **Violation:** Critical only if **Rule 37** file is skipped when HandsOff was run, or if the user ran **`/report`** / **`/feedback`** / explicitly requested a saved report or feedback file and it was omitted — not when you omit optional on-disk summaries
   
   ### Rule 0.7: MANDATORY English for Project Artifacts (Not Chat)
   - **In scope (English REQUIRED):** Anything **created or modified on disk** in this workspace — file/folder names, paths, code comments, repo docs, reports under `Cursor-Project/reports/`, test cases, user stories in `User story/`, config/templates, **`.cursor/`** content, and other **persisted** project text
